Description:

Humans have characteristics and behaviors that are not much different from animals.

It is that the ability to practice logical thinking to catalyze a value system for our own selves is what make us special.

Content:

*Disclaimer: This article may appear somewhat “intolerable” to religious followers, or anyone reckoning that humans are the "most exceptional creatures in the entire universe".

_____

To all appearances, we have been reviling others as “some whippersnappers'', else associating them to "dog", "pig", and every-awful-thing-turning-up-in-their-minds. To put it simply, humans must always be the ultimate heavenly sacred creatures, who, once disparaged, could only end up some [meagre] animals.

After all, ain’t those foul-mouths zeroing in humans - the “seemingly all too heinous” species that perpetually get on our nerves? No human would ever humanly blaspheme a drab dog as "dim-witted as a human". However loathful they are, humans, as a rule, still are the most honorable creatures to us - humans.

Dismally enough, there exists no other way around. Our fellow-human inherent relationship urges us to turn others into sitting ducks beforehand; for were we to revile someone as those of the same species as ours, ain’t we talking our own names in vain?

Given its paradoxical nature, the strife can be reasoned out as: (1) we own every system of religious, political and moral dogmas to postulate that humans are born a “red-letter” species and (2) our humanly biological instincts stoke our dim-wittedness during most of our lifetime, thus henpecking others.

Since we always bear with the very preconception that we are indeed exceptional (so do I), every argument unveiling human lives as every-awful-thing-turning-up-in-their-minds, thus, would all too often get on our nerves. That said, given that agreement, could we ever turn a blind eye to the unimpeachable fact that humans, for the most part, are woefully loathsome?

But why? [Why can we appear so paradoxical?]

Here we heed the own biological bodies of ours.

1. Not all human behavior is sublime and meaningful.

This article may appear somewhat “intolerable” to religious followers, or anyone reckoning that humans are the "most exceptional products in the entire universe".

Since I reckon that the human body must have evolved in alignment with Darwin’s Evolution, we, along with every other species must bear with some similarity in physical traits, even brain’s structure, which spell out certain resemblance in behaviors.

To put into perspective, our “survival kit” still bears little difference with other species, purely revolving around eat-sleep-reproduce. Humans, under certain circumstances, also awfully hurt for food, sleep, and procreativity - akin every other species [1].

After all, even when we are under barely exceptional circumstances, humans have all too often “played” wild animals, notably our malevolent nature and insurmountable aphrodisia. Should the video of the lions clashing with each other give you butterflies and urge you to turn nose up at which, heed humans - the very creatures spearheading fights over some trivial discords, or murderous intentions upon catching a tantalizing glimpse, let alone ever other ferocious war and series of barbarous genocides.

After all, we could hardly puzzle over the falsifiability of those "bad blood" arguments, for it would appear wildly sophisticated were we to reason it out from our “human-player rules”. That said, isn’t it zeroing us in the very resemblance between humans and wild animals - between the ferocious prowess [to go up against others]? Given the contextual difference in what the “animals” fight for, how we, as well as other animals have, is kindred.

Worse still, our biological bodies have even exerted every impact on other “seemingly normal, yet all too drab” behaviors.

To put into perspective, we humans still are bearing similar expense patterns as Capuchin monkeys and other animals. Having dug deep into economic behaviors, one previous article of ours even homed us in the very fact that for the most part, Capuchins’ first expense patterns did actually resemble ours.

